'''Joshua Heschel Zoref''' (1633–1700) was a 17th-century ascetic, and an important figure in the [[Jews of Lithuania|Lithuanian]] [[Sabbatean]] movement. During the messianic fervor of 1666, he claimed to experience visions similar to those of [[Ezekiel]]. He, like [[Judah Leib Prossnitz]] also, considered himself to be possessed of the role of [[Messiah ben Joseph]], with [[Shabbatai Tzvi]] playing the role of [[Messiah ben David]].
Shortly thereafter he began transcribing his visions into five books. What has survived of these works show them to be entirely built upon the numerical speculations ([[gematriah]]) of [[Nathan Nata Spira]]. Some parts of this work, named ''Sefer Ha-Zoref'', came to [[Nathan ben Levi]], while others came into the possession of the [[Baal Shem Tov]], who evidently valued them highly while unaware of their origins.
Scholem (1974) contains a lengthier biography.
== References == *{{cite book | last = Scholem | first = Gershom G. | authorlink = Gershom Scholem | year = 1974 | title = Kabbalah | publisher = [[Keter Publishing House]] | location = Jerusalem }}
