[[File:Gilardone lotegorisch.png|thumb|right|Title page of Christian Heinrich Gilardone's Lotegorisch book, ''Parodiee, Gedichtches und prousaische Uffsätz. #Vun kaan Jüd’ - vun e Goj'', Speyer, 1835]] '''Lotegorisch''' or ''Lottegorisch'' (older own description: ''lochne kodesch'', from the {{lang-he|laschon}} = "tongue, language", and ''kodesch'' = "holy") is a trading language and [[Palatine dialects|Palatine]] variant of the secret language, [[Rotwelsch]], spoken in the [[Leiningerland]] (especially in [[Carlsberg, Germany|Carlsberg]]), where in the late 18th century a large number of [[vagrancy (people)|vagrants]], including many [[Jew]]s, were settled and where many of them worked as itinerant craftsmen and [[peddler]]s.<ref name=AM>Meißner (1999)</ref>
== References == {{Reflist}}
== Literature == *Anton Meißner: ''Die pfälzische Handelssprache Lotegorisch. Wörterbuch mit Leseproben''. Meißner Verlag, Wattenheim, 1999 (printed as a manuscript)
== External links == * [http://www.lotegorisch.de www.lotegorisch.de]
[[Category:German dialects]] [[Category:Anterior Palatinate]] [[Category:Palatinate Forest]]
{{language-stub}}

{{expand lead|date=May 2018}} '''Lumber hooker''' is a nautical term for a [[Great Lakes]] ship designed to carry her own deck load of lumber and to tow one or two [[barges]]. The barges were [[schooner barge]]s: large old [[schooners]] stripped of their [[mast (sailing)|masts]] and running gear to carry large cargoes of lumber.<ref>*{{cite book| last= Boyer | first = Dwight| title= Great Stories of the Great Lakes: Thrilling Tales of Tragedy, Humor, and Heroism| publisher = Freshwater Press, Inc. | year= 1996| location = Cleveland, Ohio, USA| isbn = 0-912514-49-3}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Consort (nautical)]] *''[[Orin W. Angwall]]'' *[[SS Myron|SS ''Myron'']]
