{{For|the Gaudiya Nritya dancer|Mahua Mukherjee}}
{{no footnotes|date=November 2011}}
{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}
'''Dr. Mohua Mukherjee''' (born August 1952) is a social activist and an author from [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]. She was schooled at Gokhale Memorial School, Kolkata. She married Alok Mukherjee in 1974. Her achievements include social activism, writing, documentary and short film making, artistry, theatre work and socio-economic research about tribes of [[India]]. She is also founder of a [[non-governmental organization]] named "Sanyog Audio Visual and Welfare Society".

==Career==
After marriage she took a freelance job at Hotel Oberoi Grand–Kolkata as an interior decorator. She joined St. Thomas Kidderpore as an art teacher. She started an [[art school]] at home for children, named ‘Rekhae Chonde’. She combined the art school with Indian classical dancing, the combination called "Rekahe" (for painting) and "Chonde" (for dancing). She also created a ‘Dance Drama Group" in Kolkata named "Roopkatha".<!-- Comment: THIS NEXT SENTENCE IS NOT UNDERSTANDABLE WHAT DOES IT MEAN?: and started many Drama & [[dance drama]] (most of it written by her and all of them directed by her) with a team of 12 to 20 accompanies-->.

She started social work through projects in conjunction with [[UNICEF]],  [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]], [[WILD (social work organization)|WILD]], AIIPH, [[World Health Organization]] and India-Canada Environment Facility (ICEF) through her own [[NGO]] named "Sanyog Audio Visual and Welfare Society", which focuses on issues such as homelessness and health. in urban and rural areas of [[West Bengal]]. She developed an interest on Tribal life and joined the movement for the welfare of tribes in rural Bengal and adjacent areas.

She also began working in [[journalism]] and has been published in newspapers and magazines such as “Ulto Rath”, “Shanonda”, “AnandaBazar Patrika”, “Bartaman” and “AajKaal”.

Books written by Mukherjee include ''Lal Maati Shaal Bon'', ''Gohin Manush He'', ''Chandoi Birhor'' and ''Birhor towards next Millennium''. <!-- Comment: WHAT DOES THIS MEAN?: She bid her goodbye leaving all options open for her unfinished work's development on 27 June 2009.-->

