{{Infobox language |name=Pemako Tshangla |nativename=པདྨ་བཀོད་ཚངས་ལ་སྐད |pronunciation={{IPA|[tsʰaŋla]}} |region=[[Pemako]] region, [[Tibet]]; [[Arunachal Pradesh]], [[India]] |speakers=10,000-15,000 |date= 2012 |ref={{citation needed|date=January 2013}} |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]] ? |fam3=[[Bodish languages|Bodish]] |fam4=[[Tshangla language|Tshangla]] |script=[[Tibetan alphabet]] |isoexception=dialect |glotto=none |notice=IPA }} {{Contains Tibetan text}} The '''[[Pemako|Pemakö]] dialect''' ({{bo|t=པདྨ་བཀོད་ཚངས་ལ་སྐད་|w=pad ma bkod btsang la skad}} , also ''Padma bkod skad'') is a dialect of the [[Tshangla language]]. It is the predominant speech in the Pemako region of the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]] and an adjoining contiguous area south of the [[McMahon]] line in [[Arunachal Pradesh]] in [[India]]. Though Tshangla is not a [[Tibetic languages|Tibetic language]], it shares many similarities with [[Classical Tibetan]], particularly in its [[vocabulary]]. Many Tibetan loanwords are used in Pemako, due to centuries of close contact with various [[Tibetan people|Tibetan tribes]] in the Pemako area. Pemako Tshangla has undergone tremendous changes due to its isolation and Tibetan influence.
==Phonology== Below appears a table of Tshangla consonants according to Andvik (2010). Non-native phonemes, in parentheses, are contrasted only marginally with native sounds: /ɬ/ is often nativized to /l/; /dz/ becomes /z/; and /ʑ/ becomes /y/.<ref name=Andvik>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Sc9XZ2jJGgC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Grammar of Tshangla |volume=10 |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |series=Tibetan Studies Library |first=Erik E. |last=Andvik |year=2010 |isbn=90-04-17827-9}}</ref>{{rp|8–12}}
{| class="wikitable" |+Tshangla consonants !colspan=2|&nbsp; ![[Labial consonant|Labial]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] ![[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- align=center !colspan=2|[[Approximant]] |{{IPA|w}} /w/ ཝ | | |{{IPA|j}} /y/ ཡ | |{{IPA|h}} /h/ ཧ |- align=center !colspan=2|[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |{{IPA|m}} /m/ མ |{{IPA|n}} /n/ ན | |{{IPA|ɲ}} /ny/ ཉ |{{IPA|ŋ}} /ng/ ང | |- align=center !rowspan=3|[[Plosive consonant|Plosive]] !<small>[[voiceless consonant|voiceless]]</small> |{{IPA|p}} /p/ པ |{{IPA|t}} /t/ ཏ |{{IPA|ʈ}} /tr/ ཏྲ | |{{IPA|k}} /k/ ཀ | |- align=center !<small>[[aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]]</small> |{{IPA|pʰ}} /ph/ ཕ |{{IPA|tʰ}} /th/ ཐ |{{IPA|ʈʰ}} /thr/ ཐྲ | |{{IPA|kʰ}} /kh/ ཁ | |- align=center !<small>[[voiced consonant|voiced]]</small> |{{IPA|b}} /b/ བ |{{IPA|d}} /d/ ད |{{IPA|ɖ}} /dr/ དྲ | |{{IPA|ɡ}} /g/ ག | |- align=center !rowspan=2|[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] !<small>[[voiceless consonant|voiceless]]</small> | |{{IPA|ts}} /ts/ ཅ | | {{IPA|tɕ}} /tsh/ ཆ | | |- align=center !<small>[[voiced consonant|voiced]]</small> | |({{IPA|dz}} /dz/ ཛ) | | {{IPA|dʑ}} /j/ ཇ | | |- align=center !rowspan=2|[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] !<small>voiceless</small> | |{{IPA|s}} /s/ ས | | {{IPA|ɕ}} /sh/ ཤ | | |- align=center !<small>voiced</small> | | {{IPA|z}} /z/ ཟ | | ({{IPA|ʑ}} /zh/ ཞ) | | |- align=center !rowspan=2|[[Lateral consonant|Lateral]] !<small>voiceless</small> | |({{IPA|ɬ}} /lh/ ལྷ) | | | | |- align=center !<small>voiced</small> | |{{IPA|l}} /l/ ལ | | | | |- align=center !colspan=2|[[Flap consonant|Flap]] | |{{IPA|r}} /r/ ར | | | | |} The above table generally describes onset consonants. Consonant clusters in the onset position are limited to consonant plus /r/, with the exception of the syllable /pɕi/, used on only two contexts. <ref group=nb>The cluster /pɕi/ is used only in the words for "four" (/pɕi/) and "to [[flatulence|fart]]" (/pɕi pʰule/).</ref><ref name=Andvik/>{{rp|14–15}} Intervocalic positioning of aspirated onsets /pʰ/ /tʰ/, and /kʰ/ results in [[lenition]] to /ɸ/, /θ/, and /x/ or /h/, respectively, with some exceptions.<ref name=Andvik/>{{rp|10}} Syllable-final consonants are limited to /p/, /t/, /k/, /s/, /m/, /n/, and /ŋ/.<ref name=Andvik/>{{rp|16}}
Tshangla vowels appear in the chart below, following Andvik (2010). Vowels in parentheses appear in non-native words inherited from [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]], [[Dzongkha]], and the latter's archaic liturgical form, [[Classical Tibetan|Chöke]]. Non-native front rounded vowels may be nativized as front unrounded vowels.<ref name=Andvik/>{{rp|12–14}} {| class="wikitable" |+Tshangla vowels ! !colspan=2 |[[Front vowel|Front]] ! [[Central vowel|Central]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] |- align="center" ! ! Unrounded ! Rounded | ! Rounded |- align="center" ![[Close vowel|Close]] |{{IPA|i}} /i/ ི |({{IPA|y}} /ü/ ུ) | |{{IPA|u}} /u/ ུ |- align="center" ![[Mid vowel|Mid]] |{{IPA|e}} /e/ ེ |({{IPA|œ}} /ö/ ོ) | |{{IPA|o}} /o/ ོ |- align="center" ![[Open vowel|Open]] | | |{{IPA|a}} /a/ | |} {| class="wikitable" |+Tshangla [[personal pronoun]]s ! ! Singular ! Dual ! Plural |- align="center" ! 1p | ''jang'' | ''a-ching'' | ''ai'' |- align="center" ! 2p | ''nang'' | ''na-ching'' | ''na'' |- align="center" ! 3p | ''ro'' | ''da-ching'' | ''rokte'' |}
==Formation== Ever since [[Pemako]] was first opened to outside world thousands of people from different walks of life settled in the region, among them, earliest were the [[Tshangla]] people from [[Trashigang District|Eastern Bhutan]] who fled their homeland and took refuge there. Among the first clans of Tshangla people were the Ngatsangpas (Snga Tsang pa)who paved ways for others to join them in their plight for a promised land free from sufferings. The exodus of Tshangla community continued from the beginning of the 17th century until the early 20th century. Political and religious turmoil in Tibet forced many Tibetans to join Tshangla people in Pemako a land where religious serenity pledge through many revered Lamas who had been to this land, prophesied by [[Padmasambhava|Guru Rinpoche]] in the mid 8th century to be a land of final call where devotees would be flocking at the time of Religious persecutions, the last sanctuary for Buddhism, with the time Pemako's popularity grew more and more, with the popularity many [[Tibetan people]] particularly from [[Kham]] followed their [[lama]]s and settled alongside Tshangla populace. Over the period of time Tibetans and Tshangla migrants [[amalgamation (race)|amalgamated]] to form an homogeneous group called Pemako pas ( Pad-ma dkod pa). The process of infusion gave birth to a new Tshangla dialect called [[Pemako Tshangla language|Pemako dialect]]. People who reside in Pemako enclave are of mixed blood originated from early Tshangla settlers and different [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]] tribes, [[Standard Tibetan]] is also spoken in Pemako, with many different languages such [[Khams Tibetan language|Khampa language]], [[Kongpo|Kongpo dialect]], [[Bomê County|Poba Language]] etc.
==Number of speakers== There are approximately 10,000 [[Pemako|Tshangla]] speaker in Upper [[Pemako]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]], 4000–5000 in Lower [[Upper Siang District|Pemako]], in [[Arunachal Pradesh]] and approximately 3500–4000 [[Tibetan diaspora|Tibetan Tshangla community]] residing in three different Tibetan settlements, [[Tezu]], [[Miao, Changlang|Miao]] in [[Arunachal Pradesh]] and [[Orissa, India|Orissa]]. Many Pemakos in the past have spread to western countries as well.
