{{Infobox language |name=Phuan |nativename= |states=[[Laos]], [[Thailand]] |ethnicity=[[Phuan people]] |speakers={{sigfig|307,000|1}} |date=2000–2006 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Kradai |fam1=[[Kra–Dai languages|Kra–Dai]] |fam2=[[Tai languages|Tai]] |fam3=[[Southwestern Tai languages|Southwestern]] (Thai) |fam4=Chiang Saen |iso3=phu |glotto=phua1239 |glottorefname=Phuan }}
'''Phuan''' is a [[Tai languages|Tai language]] spoken in [[Laos]], [[Thailand]] and Cambodia.<ref name=Ethnologue>{{cite web|title=Phuan|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/language/phu|website=Ethnologue|accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Schliesinger|first1=Joachim|title=Ethnic Groups of Cambodia, Volume 3: Profile of the Austro-Thai-and Sinitic-Speaking Peoples|date=8 October 2011|publisher=White Lotus Co Ltd|isbn=9744801794|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=ayUjBgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA46&dq=Phuan+in+Banteay+Meancheay+Province,+Cambodia&ots=uz9hejuDc0&sig=5vxeZzUj0aTiaEz7jqDEuHaF_L4#v=onepage&q=Phuan%20in%20Banteay%20Meancheay%20Province%2C%20Cambodia&f=false|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>
==Distribution== In Thailand, Phuan is spoken in Chachoengsao, Chaiyaphum, Lopburi, Nakhon Nayok, Phetchabun, Phichit, Prachinburi, and Saraburi provinces; it is also spoken in an isolated area of [[Bueng Kan Province]], and in one village south of Bangkok (''Ethnologue'').
There are approximately 5,000 Phuan in [[Mongkol Borei District]] of [[Banteay Meanchey Province]] in [[Cambodia]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schliesinger|first1=Joachim|title=Ethnic Groups of Cambodia, Volume 3: Profile of the Austro-Thai-and Sinitic-Speaking Peoples|date=8 October 2011|publisher=White Lotus Co Ltd|isbn=9744801794|page=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=ayUjBgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA46&dq=Phuan+in+Banteay+Meancheay+Province,+Cambodia&ots=uz9hejuDc0&sig=5vxeZzUj0aTiaEz7jqDEuHaF_L4#v=onepage&q=Phuan%20in%20Banteay%20Meancheay%20Province%2C%20Cambodia&f=false|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> as well in [[Battambang Province]].
