{{Infobox language |name=Wanka Quechua |nativename=Wanka Nunashimi |states=[[Perú]] |speakers=23,000 Shawsha Wanka |date=1962 census |speakers2=250,000 Waylla Wanka (2002) |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Quechua languages|Quechua]] |fam2=[[Quechua I|Central]] (Quechua I) |lc1=qvw|ld1=[[Huancayo Province|Waylla&nbsp;Wanka]] |lc2=qxw|ld2=[[Jauja province|Shawsha (Jauja) Wanka]] |glotto=jauj1237 |glottorefname=Jauja–Huanca }}
'''Wanka Quechua''' is a variety of the [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] language, spoken in the southern part of [[Peru]]vian region of [[Junín region|Junín]] by the [[Huancas]].
Wanka Quechua belongs to [[Quechua I]], like [[Ancash Quechua]]. It has about 300,000 speakers and three main dialects: Waylla Wanka in [[Huancayo]] and Chupaca provinces, Waycha Wanka in [[Concepción Province, Peru|Concepción]] and Shawsha Wanka in [[Jauja]]. [[Rodolfo Cerrón Palomino]], a native Wanka speaker, published the first Wanka grammar and dictionary in 1977.
